    "id": "full_credit_desk_market",
    "description": "Chained Track A plan: three sequential calibration steps produce the full set of credit-pricing curves in a single calibrate() call. Step 1 bootstraps the USD-OIS discount curve from deposit and IRS quotes (same quotes as 01_usd_discount.json). Step 2 calibrates the CDX.NA.IG.46 index hazard curve from par-spread CDS quotes. \u26a0 The CDS spreads here are SYNTHETIC AND UNREALISTICALLY TIGHT (0.06/0.15/0.32/0.44/0.60 bp at 1Y/3Y/5Y/7Y/10Y, vs realistic CDX-IG-46 levels of 50\u2013120 bp). The synthetic spreads produce SP(5Y)\u22480.9997 \u2014 essentially zero default probability \u2014 because the chained tranche calibration in step 3 needs the hazard curve to keep the base correlation solver well-bracketed. Real-world envelopes should use realistic spreads (see 04_cdx_ig_hazard.json for the realistic shape) and recompute self-consistent tranche upfronts. Step 3 solves for the CDX-IG-46 base correlation smile from 5 tranche upfront quotes that are self-consistent with the step-2 bootstrapped hazard (quotes were generated by pricing each tranche against the chained market). FX cross rates (EUR/USD, USD/JPY, GBP/USD) are carried in initial_market.fx as a snapshot \u2014 they survive into the final MarketContext unchanged. A placeholder CDX-NA-IG-46 hazard curve in initial_market is required because the credit_indices entry must reference an existing hazard curve at context-load time; step 2 overwrites it with the bootstrapped curve. The USD-OIS placeholder has been removed \u2014 step 1 produces the discount curve entirely from quotes. A seed base_correlation curve and credit_indices entry in initial_market are required by the base correlation solver (see 05_cdx_base_correlation.json). This envelope demonstrates the canonical 'analyst's morning bootstrap' STRUCTURE for a credit desk; consumers should swap in realistic spreads + tranche quotes for production use.",
